#Text=Christiane Lemke
#Text=Christiane
#Text=Lemke
#Text=Christiane
#Text=Lemke
#Text=is a professor of political science .

#Text=She holds the chair in international relations and European studies at the University of Hanover . [ 1 ] In 1991-1992 , she was a Visiting Krupp Chair in the department of government at Harvard University and from 2010 to 2014 she held the Max Weber Chair at New York University . [ 2 ]
#Text=Lemke was the first woman in Germany to serve as the director of the state parliament in Lower Saxony . [ 3 ]
#Text=Education
#Text=Christiane Lemke studied sociology , psychology and political science and went on to earn her Ph.D. in philosophy at the Free University of Berlin . [ 3 ]
#Text=In 1983-84 she was a John F. Kennedy Memorial Fellow at the Minda de Gunzburg Center for European Studies at Harvard University .
#Text=She completed her Habilitation in 1989 at the Freie Universität Berlin and received the venia legendi in political science . [ 3 ]
#Text=Academic work
#Text=In her early work , Lemke studied East Germany , including the developments leading up to the fall of the Wall .
#Text=Together with Gary Marks she wrote “ The Crisis of Socialism in Europe ” ( Duke University Press , 1991 ) reflecting upon the sweeping changes brought about by the collapse of communism . [ 4 ]
#Text=Subsequently , she devoted her work to the democratic transformation of East Central European countries , the integration of Europe , citizenship , and the enlargement of the European Union .
#Text=She is the author of “ Internationale Beziehungen .

#Text=Grundkonzepte , Theorien und Problemfelder “ ( 4th edition , de Gruyter Oldenbourg , 2018 ) and Germany Today . Politics and Policies in a Changing World ( with Helga Welsh , Rowman and Littlefield , 2018 ) .

#Text=She also published several articles on the European Union and edited the series “ Europe as a Political Space ” ( LIT Verlag ) with publications on human rights and migration in Europe and European common defense and security policy .
#Text=She has also published articles and books on transatlantic relations , US politics and US elections .
#Text=She is a frequent commentator on German radio and TV , including Phoenix TV , ARD and ZDF as well as in international news media .
#Text=Christiane Lemke was the director of the Jean Monnet European Center of Excellence at Leibniz University Hannover where she held the Jean Monnet Chair .
#Text=She was a DAAD visiting professor at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill where she taught as adjunct professor in the Transatlantic Masters ’ program . [ 5 ]
#Text=She was also a Distinguished Visiting Professor at Suffolk University in Boston .
#Text=In 2019 , she was a visiting scholar at Harvard University . [ 6 ]
#Text=She lectured at the University Cambridge and at universities in Paris , Siena , Stockholm , Warsaw and the Institute for Human Sciences in Vienna .
#Text=In addition , she has traveled extensively in Asia and the Pacific , including China , India , Nepal , Japan , Australia and New Zealand .
#Text=Other accomplishments
#Text=In 2000 , Christiane Lemke was one of the founding professors for the International Women ’s University ( ifu ) in Hanover , Germany .
#Text=In 2010 , she was a finalist in the elections for president of the Freie Universität Berlin . [ 7 ]
